  <p>Melbourne's chimney sweeping season has a fairly predictable pattern. Knowing when demand peaks — and when it doesn't — means you can book on your terms rather than scrambling for an appointment when the cold arrives.</p>

  <h2>The Short Answer: Book in March, April or Early May</h2>

  <p>The ideal window for booking a chimney sweep in Melbourne is <strong>late summer through to early autumn</strong> — roughly March to early May. This is when:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Chimney sweeps have availability and can usually fit you in within a week or two</li>
    <li>You'll have time to address any issues found during the inspection before winter</li>
    <li>Your fire is ready to go the moment the first cold night arrives in May</li>
  </ul>

  <p>It's also when the work is easier — climbing around roofs and dealing with flues in the mild autumn weather is considerably more pleasant than mid-winter, and a good tradie will take the same amount of care, but the logistics are smoother all round.</p>

  <h2>What Happens If You Leave It Until Winter</h2>

  <p>Every year in Melbourne, the first genuinely cold snap in May or early June triggers a rush of chimney sweep bookings. Homeowners who haven't thought about it all summer suddenly want their chimney done urgently, often because they've lit the fire for the first time and noticed smoke or a poor draw.</p>

  <p>During this peak period — roughly May through July — wait times for a chimney sweep can stretch to two to four weeks. If your fire is unusable in the meantime, that's a cold house for longer than it needed to be.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>Booking in autumn means you're not competing with a wave of other Melbourne homeowners who all want the same service at the same time.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Is It Too Late If You're Already in Winter?</h2>

  <p>No — even if you're reading this in June or July, it's absolutely worth booking. A chimney that needs cleaning should be cleaned, regardless of the season. Operating a fireplace with heavy creosote buildup or a blockage is a safety risk, and getting it sorted mid-winter is far better than using it in an unsafe state.</p>

  <p>Just expect that wait times will be longer and flexibility around scheduling will be reduced during peak periods.</p>

  <h2>What About End of Season — August or September?</h2>

  <p>Booking a clean at the end of winter rather than before it is an option, but it's not ideal. The logic of cleaning after the season is that you're removing the creosote before it sits in the chimney all summer. That makes sense in principle.</p>

  <p>The downside is that if anything is found during the inspection that needs repair — cracked flue tiles, damaged mortar, a compromised liner — it'll sit unresolved until you get it fixed, and you may not think about it again until autumn anyway.</p>

  <p>If you can only do one, before winter is the more practical choice for most Melbourne households.</p>

  <h2>What to Do Before the Sweep Arrives</h2>

  <p>A chimney sweep doesn't require much preparation from your side, but a few things help:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Make sure the fire hasn't been used in the 24 hours before the appointment — a cold fireplace is easier and safer to work in</li>
    <li>Clear a reasonable space around the firebox so the tradie can lay dust sheets and work comfortably</li>
    <li>If you've noticed anything unusual — smoke, smell, poor draw — mention it when you book so it can be factored into the time allowed</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How Far in Advance Should You Book?</h2>

  <p>In the March–April window, a week or two in advance is usually plenty. By mid-May, you may be looking at two to three weeks. In June and July at peak, some operators are booked out four weeks or more.</p>

  <p>If you're reading this in late summer or autumn, the best time to book is now — you'll get the date that works for you, and your fire will be ready when Melbourne's winter reminds you why you have one.</p>
